[2]
Date: 25 Sep 2007
Source: Victoria's Harness Racing Organization [edited]
<http://www.harness.org.au/news/view_news.cfm?news_id=7601>

Following a meeting last night with Victoria's Chief Veterinary
Officer, Dr. Hugh Millar, Harness Racing Victoria (HRV) has been
advised that it won't be permitted to vaccinate its racehorse and
breeding population against Equine Influenza (EI) in the foreseeable future.
Dr. Millar advised that the National Management Group (NMG) on the EI
outbreak remained committed to eradicating the disease from
Australia's equine population and whilst this was the case mass
vaccinations amongst all breeds would not occur.
"Dr Millar advised that the national policy was still to contain and
eradicate the disease from the equine population and as such the
primary aim of vaccination was to do this through the creation of
buffer or containment zones," HRV Chief Executive, John Anderson, said.
"Until such time as there is a policy change from the NMG and state
veterinary officers and they decide that the disease cannot be
eradicated and is here to stay forever, then we have been informed
there will be no mass vaccinations of the equine population.
"The first batch of 20 000 vaccines will arrive on Thursday [27 Sep
2007] and the absolute majority of these will be used to create these
buffer zones in New South Wales and Queensland.
"Racing Victoria have been promised 1500 vials to vaccinate selected
horses as an insurance policy for the Spring Carnival, however they
requested 14 000 vaccines and were knocked back because the priority
remains the containment and eradication of EI north of the border."
The initial shipment of 20 000 vaccines from France will be followed
by a further 30 000 next week [1-5 Oct 2007] and an additional 100
000 at a yet to be determined date. All have been ordered with the
primary objective of eradicating EI from New South Wales and Queensland.
Dr. Millar advised that the Department of Primary Industries (DPI)
would not be accepting horses into Victoria from New South Wales or
Queensland for the foreseeable future, irrespective of whether they
have been vaccinated or not during the containment exercise.
Dr. Millar also implored harness racing participants to remain
vigilant despite Victoria having no reported cases of EI and
encouraged horse owners and trainers to contact the DPI immediately
if their horse was showing signs of a respiratory illness. The DPI EI
hotline is 1 800 678 779.
